    <node id="claim:0004">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d29">Rowan built a tool that generates synthetic records/PDFs, then resorts them by deleting pages, inserting new pages, rearranging pages, and splitting pages.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.95</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">178.0</data>
      <data key="d1">Rowan built a synthetic PDF generator and page-resorting tool</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "So basically, I generate PDFs, then I resort them. So I've got another command that does some resorting, which does a bunch of different things.", "ts": 178.0, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "So it deletes pages, it inserts new pages, it rearranges pages, it splits pages, it splits pages and all of that.", "ts": 191.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:02"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0005">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d29">Rowan built a matching engine that uses different matching styles to try to figure out what happened to each page, and reports how reliable each mechanism is at finding what happened to a page.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.9</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">225.0</data>
      <data key="d1">Rowan built a multi-method page-matching engine</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "And then I've got a matching engine, which uses different styles of matching to try and figure out what happened to each page.", "ts": 225.0, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "And so the output of that is using the different mechanisms, like how reliable are they in finding what happened to a page?", "ts": 227.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:02"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0006">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d29">Once the matching engine correctly identifies the right page, the Apprise Viewer manages to apply moved annotations/redactions correctly.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.9</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">236.0</data>
      <data key="d1">Apprise Viewer correctly reapplies annotations once the matching page is known</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "And then after that, based on that knowledge, I then have used the Apprise Viewer to, like, move annotations around or move redactions around just to kind of see if that works.", "ts": 236.0, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "Once you know that you've got the page, the right page, it manages to apply them correctly.", "ts": 238.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:02"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0007">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d29">When ingesting annotations in their native format (XFDF), the product already uses the Apprise engine to apply them to pages.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:deon-kuhn</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.9</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">247.0</data>
      <data key="d1">Apprise engine already applies ingested XFDF annotations to pages</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "As a quick note, when we ingest, obviously, the annotations, because they're in that format, the XFDF or whatever, we do, like, use the engine of Apprise to apply them to the pages. So that's correct as well.", "ts": 247.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:02"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0008">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d29">The content-hashing matcher can tell that two near-duplicate pages (identical except a small A/B footer difference) are not the same page, but the perceptual-hash matcher is likely to judge them as the same page and miss the small difference.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.9</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">305.0</data>
      <data key="d1">Exact-hash catches an A/B footer difference; perceptual hash likely misses it</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "the matcher that matches on hashing the content will be able to determine that these are not the same page.", "ts": 300.0, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "It's been like, oh, these still look like the same page. But then it doesn't pick up little tiny things like that.", "ts": 305.0, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:02"]</data>
    </node>
