      <data key="d9">["chapter:03"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0012">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Stamped ID survived page reinsertion, naturally the strongest identifier</data>
      <data key="d29">The metadata stamp survived Rowan's page-insertion/resorting method and was naturally the strongest way of identifying the original page.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.9</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">885.9</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "I did that stamp, and that survived at least my method of inserting new pages and whatever. And so that obviously was naturally the strongest way of identifying the original.", "ts": 885.9, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0013">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Exact hash: 92.9% precision on confident pages</data>
      <data key="d29">Exact hash matching got 92.9% of its confident (non-abstained) page-outcome predictions right.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.95</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">971.8</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "Of those that it was confident about, it got 92.9% right, which is good, right?", "ts": 971.8, "source": "transcript"}, {"quote": "exact_hash      P 92.9% R 89.7% abst-ok 81.2% silent 5.6% / queue 22.2%", "ts": 946.5, "source": "vision"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0014">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Exact hash only works on text-bearing / clean pages</data>
      <data key="d29">Exact hash matching only works for pages that have text, or clean-looking pages.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:deon-kuhn</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.9</data>
      <data key="d32">opinion</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">982.1</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "But that only works for things that maybe have text. Or clean-looking things, yeah.", "ts": 982.1, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0015">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Exact hash fails badly on split pages</data>
      <data key="d29">Exact hash is really bad at detecting a split page: because the two resulting pages don't hash the same, it thinks the original page is simply gone.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.9</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">1002.1</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "So anyway, it's really bad at split. So actually, if a page has been split, it basically thinks the page is gone because there's nothing that's, those two pages don't hash.", "ts": 1002.1, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0016">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Stamped route is by far the best, removes matching noise</data>
      <data key="d29">Going with the stamped-ID route is by far and above the best approach: it gets rid of all the noise involved in trying to figure out the right matching.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.9</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">1047.7</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "And then, basically, the conclusion is that if we go stamped, like, the stamped route is by far and above, like, it gets rid of all the crazy noise and trying to figure out, like, how to do the right matching.", "ts": 1047.7, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0017">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
      <data key="d1">Stamped approach only errs on true duplicates or unlinked splits</data>
      <data key="d29">The stamped approach only gets it wrong when a page has been exactly duplicated without re-stamping, or split without any lineage recorded into the previous page; every other scenario it catches because the metadata stamping is maintained.</data>
      <data key="d30">person:rowan-reid</data>
      <data key="d31">[]</data>
      <data key="d7">0.9</data>
      <data key="d32">fact</data>
      <data key="d33">False</data>
      <data key="d28">1052.8</data>
      <data key="d8">[{"quote": "Like, if you do stamped, it works, and the only time it gets it wrong is if you've got a exact, like, a duplicate, like, you literally have duplicated the page, and now it's there twice with the same ID, and you haven't re-stamped. Or you've split a page, and you haven't put any kind of lineage into the previous page. Every other scenario, it obviously catches, because you've maintained the metadata stamping.", "ts": 1052.8, "source": "transcript"}]</data>
      <data key="d9">["chapter:04"]</data>
    </node>
    <node id="claim:0018">
      <data key="d0">Claim</data>
